column59: Thank you so much for doing this! As a nonbinary person, i'm in a constant state of struggle with my identity. Not that i'm unsure of my own identity but rather a struggle with the constant lack of recognition that my gender even exists – in even the most everyday of language, e.g. "he or she" or "ladies and gentlemen." It's caused me to believe that i don't deserve to exist and sometimes even wonder whether i really exist at all or not. I most often see nonbinary erasure in surveys and forms, too, when they ask for gender but only give the two binary options, so it is so very refreshing to not only come across a survey that not only gives an applicable option but is about and for spreading data that shows nonbinary exists. Thank you so much. -  - I don't mind if you use any of the above for this project (assuming you even use anything written in the feedback box as data), but i do have one request: please don't "correct" my lowercase i's if you do. I don't capitalize them for the personal reason that generally, only important things are capitalized in English, and i am not one of those things. It probably sounds like a silly thing to stress, but i feel that if my i's were to be capitalized in a quote, even for the sake of grammar, it would be a misquote. -  - Again, thank you so much for recognizing other genders and for doing this project!

column30: In a world where nonbinary people were accepted, I'd probably prefer an explicitly nonbinary title (as opposed to a gender-inclusive one like Mx), but with the way the political climate's going, I'm becoming more hesitant about anything that would officially state that I'm nonbinary.
column48: I like "nonbinary" myself, but I'm also aware that some people (especially POC) take issue with using a term that references the gender binary at all, so I don't know that I can wholeheartedly recommend it.I'm not sure what other candidates I *do* recommend though - I know I really hate it when "genderfluid" gets used as an umbrella term (fluidity is a specific experience that *isn't* shared by everyone who isn't binary!).  And I'm not a fan of "genderqueer" as an umbrella because some people seem to use it to mean "gender non-conforming", and whilst that's fine, it's still different to having a nonbinary identity and I think that's an important distinction. "Gender diverse" and "gender creative" both feel patronising to me, but maybe I could get over that.

column48: I personally think nonbinary is a good umbrella term as it by definition includes everything outside the binary, but there might be (and probably are) people who don't want themselves associated with that word for reasons presently unknown to me and would feel uncomfortable with them being included in its use. I do currently use it as I have not seen people against its use and have no better alternative at this time. I think we do need an umbrella term to ease communication, especially in making informational content for people not familiar with there being more than two genders. The posts I read on the internet were essential in understanding my own gender but the amount of scattered and sometimes conflicting information made it all hard to process.

column59: I'm sure this has come up before, but I still strongly believe it's worth analysing and being critical about the different experiences that nonbinary people have based on their birth assignment. I understand that's in some ways antithetical to the nature of a nonbinary survery. I suppose people see it as maybe trying to say something inherent about people based on their assignment but it's more that it's looking for the ways OTHER people treat you based on your assignment that can lead to differences in action. Your experience of life is (unfortunately) in part inherent to your birth assignment because that will have affected so much of how you were raised (even if you had the most trans aware and accepting parents ever, you will still have various interactions in a oft-viciously cisnormative society). Until this is acknowledged and analysed in detail, rather than remaining some rarely spoken of undercurrent, we have little hope of overcoming gender oppression. People might worry that we discover strong trends among particular assignments, and that this will be used to create some scientific justification for actions based on assignment, but no, it's so that we can then ask why society leads people to those trends, and work to understand and overcome.

column48: I find non binary worked and continues to work for me. As an umbrella term, it introduced me to the idea of gender outside of the binary, which I had thought to be the only choices growing up. Researching the more specific terms under non binary lead to my current gender identity, but even at my most questioning or dysphoric I go back to NB as the fundamental principle of how I think of my own gender.It has also served as a conceptual base for starting to understand identities other than the ones I identify with. Thinking of gender identity as a spectrum, both in what aspects of gender expression, experience and concept one identifies with, and how that identity may evolve over time, has been an important tool in staying open to other people's experience of gender. And that for me is summarized in my understanding of non binary identities. As soon as gender is not all or naught, learning and understanding the many ways that gender can be experienced and understood is just a question of time and willingness to keep learning.

column59: The only reason that an umbrella term is needed at all is that our culture assumes that "normal" is to be unipolar on a binary scale. However, any umberella term seems to be merely an opt out from that limitation rather than a positive statement of identity -  - The term "cisgender" describes that identity well. Unfortunately "trans*", even with the asterix to distinguish it from "trans" still implies a single transition "from here to there" -  - The main problem with "non binary" (like atheist) is that it describes what "I am not" as opposed to what "I am". It does not feel right to me to define myself by a negative.  -  -

column59: I am a GQ physician who evaluates and/or provides CHT/HRT to GQ/TG/GNC individuals.  My office policy is for my clients to be happy and healthy - no matter what that means.   - Personally, I feel like I am next-gen progressive in that any term, as long as not outright derogatory, which describes or defines non-gender-binary folks, would be acceptable.  Too many peeps, IMO, miss the forest for the trees when they protest well-intentioned people, trying to be inclusive, inadvertently use a term which may be upsetting to some. - I feel, if there is no malice in their <a cis-straight person] heart, AND if one is secure in their non-gender-binary identity, we, as a community of non-gender-binary people need to be more forgiving.  Let's do more outreach, more education, more social-based research, and a lot less complaining and protesting. - Is protesting and complaining sometimes needed?  Absolutely, yes!  However, I'd like to see and hear ... more positive press for our social situation and less negativity. - Have I ever told anyone the above?  ABSOLUTELY NOT!  I am one member and active advocate/ally who does not want to be lambasted.  - My Pooh Sense, - LO'

column48: I think having an umbrella term is a good idea, but there's such variance among the non-binary community that any term with a definition other than "not 100% male or 100% female" will - by its very nature - alienate and exclude a set of people. Non-binary on its own is a good overall umbrella due to its inclusive nature, and while the various listings on page one of this survey make for an excellent starting point at categorical subdivision? They should by no means be The Only Non-Binary Choices - a HUGE part of my lived experience has been discovering who I am for myself, and I'm VERY hesitant about anything that may lead to others like me feeling like they HAVE to be something they're not.

column59: Hello! This was very nice, good work all around!  - Though I understand using it in the survey because some people do identify with it, it might be good to take the trans* label out, or at least look into what makes it problematic. I'm not sure what the actual final consensus is (I'm not sure if there is one tbh), but I've seen people say that it was originally intended to exclude trans women, and later to also exclude nonbinary individuals, as the * was meant to mean exceptions that can stand with trans people, but aren't actually trans.  - Also, for intergender, may be nice to put a note next to it to make it a point that that gender is an intersex-only gender identity, as I have seen cases where dyadic/non-intersex individuals have tried to coopt the term for themselves. I'm not intersex, so I can't really put my two cents in, but I had followed an intersex blog (now inactive I think) that made a couple posts saying that they didn't want dyadic individuals using their term.  - Thank you, I hope you are having a wonderful day!! Best wishes and happy trails!!

column58: About the umbrella term: I can see good and bad things. It's a good idea because everyone who isn't cisgender 100% of the time can have common experiences with discrimination and prejudice, so a common name makes sense. But (this probably applies more to the future when we've progressed in awareness of several genders existing) splitting up into cisgender  and trans strips all of the nuance away from gender because first you're this umbrella term and then you have whatever more specific label under that.  Ad umbrella term for people who don't identify with their gender assignment stil works in the overarching idea that you're either normal or you're not i.e. Cis or trans. Like you're still thinking within the binary.

column48: Non-binary is good for now; if/when people get the hang of understanding people like us, a new word would be good. Trans is, to my mind, a nicely broad Latinate pre-fix that can cover a lot of relationships to gender and the gender one was assigned at birth, and can be used in conjunction with other modifiers to great effect (trans folks differs from my trans masc friends differs from a trans woman differs from trans androgyne). Trans can and does encompass binary genders, but I find it useful to describe the  common experience of going between, beyond, etc gender boundaries. nb and enby are nice abbreviations; gender independent is a particular thing that doesn't encompass all nb folks; genderqueer sometimes does the trick but sometimes means something specific. Gender fuckery as a noun for what we do is a handy vocabulary item. Non-binary works now, and is what I use now. If the idea of a binary fades, new words need to be figured out.

column59: I don't think "not completely male" or "not completely female" quite covers it. What has been seen as feminine or masculine varies from culture to culture and has changed throughout history within each culture. I see gender as an expression of cultural background and individuality. It is fashion, it is tradition, it's arbitrary bits and pieces of culture and behavior that for whatever reason we label as gender. Personally I don't really see the need to categorize these bits as gender because they can be described as other things (fashion, tradition, custom, "thing I enjoy doing"). I don't call myself agender because others can categorize my behavior or appearance as being gendered. But likewise, in a world where men can paint their nails and women can wear pants, I believe that people should be able to do what they want and express themselves as they wish without the need for arbitrary gender labels. Just keep on doin' what you like doin' because you are a human. And let people keep doin' what they like doin' without judging them for going against some arbitrary grain.

column58: This is a pretty good test, I'm not actually sure of it's exact purpose but i assume it's a statistics/opinion based thing. -  - my final comments would be... i notice there is a strand of, understandable and logical, thought within the trans (and further) community on,,, umbrella terms and general ease of access terms/things in general. -  - While i'm really down with making this accessible in terms of accessibility to information and for disabled folx i kind of find myself a bit leery of these actions often. -  - I don't think we should need to dumb down our identities for people outside the trans (and further) community. I think there all of this stuff needs to be taught and accessible in a respectful way so people can educate themselves on this vibrant and expansive sub community. when people talk about umbrella terms so we're easier to take or understand, there's ignoring the fact that most people don't like us anyways. even if we are the ideal trans punching bag people don't like us (for a myriad of reasons) and that's something i think we all need to accept and fight against through standing up for ourselves and educating better.  -  - Let people explore themselves and question and change their minds and use 30000 different labels and, instead of rallying against them in insipid and occasionally outright ways just? let it be. create an environment where it's safe for us all to do so and let people be people- wild, too much to explain and ultimately, fun.  -  - i'm from a rural part of Australia as an economic migrant, if you need to know any of that info btw. have a great one

column48: While cis people may eventually come to accept a third or even a fourth gender, getting them to accept a whole list of terms for every variation of gender would be next to impossible. It is clear, however, that gender isn't just binary and contains many variations. An umbrella term might be a good compromise between nonbinary people and cis people, and it would also be easier to remember. Furthermore, a lot of genders in the lists that I've seen are usually extremely similar, to the point where I question whether or not it would be a good idea to just share them all under 'nonbinary' (kind of like how every autism-related disorder is now called ASD instead of having the difference between classical autism and Asperger's [though I do not mean that being nonbinary is a mental disorder!]). Of course, everyone has a right to identify as they wish, and not everyone would be comfortable with an umbrella term, so it should be kept in mind that this is not an ideal solution by any means.

At the same time I wonder if this means you're going to get a LOT of people like me, who are...not sure. (I live my life as a woman, pretty happily, and if I weren't aware of nonbinary identities I'm not sure I would question whether I am entirely a woman. At the same time, if I could be anything I wanted to, I'd be everything. "Mommy, wouldn't it be cool if we could be a boy sometimes and a girl sometimes?" --me at age five.) So I hope my "mostly female, possibly slightly agender or nonbinary" thing doesn't throw your stats off too much. Please feel free to disregard my answers as a data point if you think I fall outside what you're looking for! -  - And you're awesome for running this survey! I hope y'all get a lot of great info.

column48: I think that for all of us who don't fit in the binary, having an umbrella term that we can use if we want helps a lot to find other people who in a certain extent share our experience. Another good thing about it is that as an umbrella term, it can cover a lot of different experiences I can have in my life. It means that whatever I find out about my own, I won't have to change the way I call myself. Other labels don't offer me that. As a person who has always lived in a binary environment, my gender is exactly what is says: what it isn't. This negative way of defining suits me, because this 'outside' cannot be defined in the affirmative. It is too large, too great. And anyway, is there an easiest way to describe who I am in a way that is, just by name, understable even by the 'layman'? I understand that some people disagree with the term, with the idea of an umbrella. But we shouldn't give up that possibility, because it is in this term that questioning people will get a first impression of what they were maybe looking for all along.

column48: From what I know, nonbinary is already used as both a personal identifier and as an umbrella term for anyone who's gender is not entirely, not always, not at all, or both male/female. However, the entire concept of a gender not falling within the gender binary makes an umbrella term pretty void - everyone's experience with being of a gender that isn't binary is different and (in the case of nb/gq/etc. ppl who consider themselves trans (or are otherwise a part of the lgbt community)) our experiences as lgbt individuals is oftentimes different as well. Any umbrella term would inevitably make some nb/gq/etc. people feel left out or uncomfortable (e.g. I personally feel extremely uncomfortable when people use "genderqueer" as an umbrella term for people who's gender isn't binary due to the use of the q slur in it). In theory it would be nice to have a universal umbrella term, if only for the sake of convenience, but in practice there already are terms and it's hard to agree on them because everyone has different experiences.

column59: I'm the assistant curator of the museum of transology (idk if you've heard of it but it's a museum dedicated to archiving the everyday objects of trans ppl so that our theirstories aren't lost). I'm also the highest up nonbinary person involved in the project so was consulted by the curator on how nonbinary is spelled (I was the only nb person in the room at the time) I insisted I was sure it was all one word but various other people in the room disagreed with me (basically everyone disagreed but none of them were nb so didn't feel they could correct me on the spelling of my identity) we ended up googling and google told us it was non-binary, so all of the literature for the museum says non-binary. It became a bit of an in-joke throughout the instal that I identified as nonbinary all one word but didn't identify with the hyphenated version. my friend sent this survey to me after I told them that story because one of the questions references spelling. Idk why I'm telling you this and I don't think I explained it especially eloquently but I thought you'd perhaps appreciate the anecdote

column48: There are many terms to describe various gender identities. I believe that these should stay, but an umbrella term can exist along side those specific terms to help people outside of the LGBTQA+ community to better understand or identify a friend/family/coworker member that identifies as such. ie: some one unfamiliar with ALL of the various terms can use/start an umbrella term to help them better understand/respect anyone that falls under that category. Baby steps. It is also good for people still questioning themselves. They can call themselves "nonbinary" and still be working out their gender identity and sill be LGBT and not feel they are not welcome or are prematurely outing themselves as a specific identity that they may not really identify with. ie: identify as a trans male, but later regret it and are actually agender. instead, they could use an umbrella term to give themselves the room to still specify their identity.

column48: Umbrella terms make it easier to talk about a specific concept, but I think we should be wary of which context we use them in and which groups of people we put under the umbrella. Umbrella terms can be problematic from a Western worldview because of the Western world's history of colonialism. There are those who may have similar experiences to for example "trans" or "nonbinary", but they fall outside the Western understanding of gender. For example Hijra are often refered to as "trans", but their understanding of gender is different than here in the West. Putting certain groups in Western umbrella terms reduces their complex experiences with gender and this can in some cases become a "colonialist" project where certain groups are forced to fit into a narrative that corresponds with a Western world view. I hope that makes sense, I'm not sure how else to describe it.

column59: The reason why I use my pronouns (Ze/Zem/Zyr/Zyrs/Zemself) instead of the traditional Ze/Hir and Xe/Xem is because they are more easy to write (I know the y's seem unconventional, but it's just more comfortable to use them instead of e and i which have connotations to typically binary pronouns) and pronounce. Also considering how I'm neurodivirgent and so are my siblings, it's easier to have pronouns that are pronounced like how they are read and don't use X which my brothers find hard to pronounce. There's also the fact that I personally pronounce them differently from the Ze/Hir and Xe/Xem set, and I just like my own set more.

column48: Well, gender is a very complicated thing. To get labels that fit every single part on the gender spectrum would be near impossible. Of course, there can (and should) be names that act sort of as "sub-categories" that describe certain parts of it (like agender, bigender, neutrosis, etc.) so people can understand their identity and feel less alone. I guess it gives off a community vibe? It's nice to know exactly what you are haha. But for some it is impossible to actually find one specific label that fits (like me), so simply going as genderqueer or nonbinary simplifies it a lot and gets rid of the need for some to try and put specific labels on something they can't explain. Genderqueer acts as a label in itself for me and others who can't explain what exactly they identitfy as. I hope this makes sense?
